V{{Libertarianism sidebar}}\u000a'''Loren E. Lomasky''' is an [[United States|American]] [[philosopher]], currently a Cory Professor of Political Philosophy, Policy and Law at the [[University of Virginia]]. Lomasky earned his PhD from the [[University of Connecticut]], and has previously taught at [[Bowling Green State University]] in [[Ohio]], the [[University of Minnesota]] in [[Duluth, Minnesota|Duluth]], and the [[Australian National University]] in [[Canberra]]. He has also been a contributing editor to ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]'' magazine.\u000a\u000aLomasky has written principally on [[ethics]] and [[political philosophy]]. His book ''Persons, Rights, and the Moral Community'' established his reputation as a leading advocate of a [[Natural-rights libertarianism|rights-based]] [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] approach to moral and social issues. Besides these, his teaching interests include the [[philosophy of religion]], [[medieval philosophy]], and other periods in the history of philosophy.\u000a\u000aLomasky has been the recipient of many awards including the 1991 Matchette Prize for his ''Persons, Rights, and the Moral Community''. Professor Lomasky has held research appointments sponsored by the NEH, the Center for the Study of Public Choice, the [[Australian National University]] and Bowling Green's Social Philosophy and Policy Center.\u000a\u000a__NOTOC__\u000a==Selected bibliography==\u000a* "When Hard Heads Collide: A Philosopher Encounters Public Choice," ''The American Journal of Economics and Sociology'', 63 (2004).\u000a* "Liberty and Welfare Goods: Reflection on Clashing Liberalisms," ''Journal of Ethics'' 4 (2000).\u000a* "Aid Without Egalitarianism: Assisting Indigent Defendants," in William C. Heffernan & John Kleinig (eds.), ''From Social Justice to Criminal Justice'', Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2000, ISBN 0-19-512985-7.\u000a* ''Democracy and Decision: The Pure Theory of Electoral Preference'', Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1993, ISBN 0-521-35043-3 (with [[Geoffrey Brennan]]).\u000a* ''Politics and Process: New Essays in Democratic Thought'', Cambridge: Cambridge University Press 1989, ISBN 0-521-35043-3 (co-editor, with Geoffrey Brennan).\u000a* ''Persons, Rights, and the Moral Community'', Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1987, ISBN 0-19-504209-3.\u000a\u000a==See also==\u000a* [[American philosophy]]\u000a* [[Libertarian views of rights]]\u000a* [[List of American philosophers]]\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a* [http://ppl.virginia.edu/lomasky Loren Lomasky's profile at University of Virginia]\u000a* [http://www.independent.org/aboutus/person_detail.asp?id=708 Lomaskys's writings at the Independent Review].\u000a* [http://www.cei.org/dyn/pubs_by_author.cfm/pubs_by_author.cfm?expert=47 Lomasky's writings at the Competitive Enterprise Institute site].\u000a* [http://www.thefreemanonline.org/author/loren-lomasky/# Lomasky's writings at the Foundation for Economic Education].\u000a* [http://www.cato.org/pubs/journal/cj5n1/cj5n1-9.pdf "Is Social Security Politically Untouchable?"]. ''[[The Cato Journal]]'', 5 (Spring/Summer 1985).\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Lomasky, Loren}}\u000a[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\u000a[[Category:Living people]]\u000a[[Category:University of Connecticut alumni]]\u000a[[Category:University of Virginia faculty]]\u000a[[Category:20th-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:American libertarians]]\u000a[[Category:American philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:American political philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Libertarian theorists]]\u000a[[Category:Cato Institute people]]
